<%# MiClassrooms Phase 4 Task 7 (Brief §5.3, §14.1): room edit — curated fields
    (nickname, ADA seat count), the three media slots
    (photo/panorama/seating_chart) with attach + remove, and gallery
    add/remove/reorder. Everything below is ONE form posting to #update,
    which routes curated-field changes and media changes through TWO
    Curation::Apply calls (RoomsController, Phase 5 Task 6) so every
    mutation here is audited.

    Phase 5 Task 6 retrofit (Brief §14.1): RoomPolicy#update?/#edit? now admit
    the room's unit editor too, so this page is no longer admin-only — but
    RoomPolicy#manage_media? stays admin-only, so the media markup (extracted
    into rooms/edit/_media_sections) renders ONLY when
    `policy(@room).manage_media?`. An editor instead sees a hint pointing them
    at notes (§14.1: editors flag media issues via notes, they don't manage
    media directly) — this is a policy-gated CONTROL, not merely hidden UI:
    the corresponding strong-params boundary in RoomsController#room_params
    is what actually stops a crafted request, this view only keeps what's
    rendered consistent with what's permitted.

    `multipart: true` is explicit (not auto-detected): TailwindFormBuilder's
    `file_field` renders via UI::FileInputComponent directly rather than
    delegating to Rails' own Tags::File, so it never flips the FormBuilder's
    `@multipart` flag the way `form_with`'s auto-detection relies on. Without
    this, the browser would submit the three media/gallery file inputs as
    empty strings (x-www-form-urlencoded), not their file contents. Harmless
    to keep `multipart: true` even for an editor who never sees a file input. %>
<% content_for(:title) { t("rooms.edit.title", room: @room.display_name) } %>

<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
  <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-text-heading"><%= t("rooms.edit.title", room: @room.display_name) %></h1>

  <%# Phase 5 Task 5 (Brief §14.1): an admin reaches this page for a HIDDEN
      room too (RoomPolicy#edit? admits admin? unconditionally, unlike an
      editor who needs the room visible) — the Unhide control belongs here
      as much as on show, since an admin fixing up a hidden room's details
      may want to re-list it from the same page. %>
  <%= render "rooms/visibility_actions", room: @room %>

  <%= form_with model: @room, url: room_path(@room), method: :patch, multipart: true,
        class: "mt-8 space-y-8" do |form| %>
    <%= form.error_summary %>

    <%= render "rooms/edit/curated_fields", form: form %>

    <% if policy(@room).manage_media? %>
      <%= render "rooms/edit/media_sections", room: @room, form: form %>
    <% else %>
      <%= ui :banner, variant: :info do %>
        <%= t("rooms.edit.media_admin_only_hint") %>
        <%= link_to t("rooms.edit.media_admin_only_hint_link"), room_path(@room),
              class: "underline underline-offset-4 hover:no-underline focus-ring rounded-sm" %>
      <% end %>
    <% end %>

    <%= form.submit t("rooms.edit.submit") %>
  <% end %>
</div>
